ce:section.ce:para:
In addition to the occurrence of GQDs in leaves, both GQDs also appeared in the stems and roots after one day of exposure, regardless of surface charge (Fig. 3
                        ). This finding indicated that once the GQDs entered the plant conductive system, they could move rapidly to the roots along the leaf-stem-root pathway within one day. In accordance with the observation on the leaves, positively charged NH2-GQDs had relatively higher abundance than negatively charged OH-GQDs in stems at any time point of exposure (P < 0.05), indicating that NH2-GQDs had higher transmission efficiency than OH-GQDs. From all FM images, approximately >80% NH2-GQDs and OH-GQDs were distributed in or near the vascular system of leaves and stems, suggesting the vascular system was the main transmission route for hydrophilic GQDs. The vascular system also constitutes the pathway for the leaf-to-root translocation of CuO NPs in the lettuce plants and carbon-coated Fe NPs in pumpkin plants (Corredor et al., 2009; Xiong et al., 2017). The phloem in vascular system has a crucial role in the leaf-to-root transportation and consolidation of the internal substances of the plant (Su et al., 2019). Therefore, the movement of GQDs might occur simultaneously with the delivery of photosynthates (sugars, proteins, etc.) along phloem. Interestingly, the number of both dispersed particles and aggregates of GQDs in the stems continued to increase over the entire exposure time, but the GQDs in the roots gradually increased within the initial 5 days and then decreased (Fig. 3). For instance, very few dispersed particles of GQDs in the roots could be observed at day 8, especially for NH2-GQDs. Reasonably, the particle sizes were observed to approach and even exceed the pipe diameter of vascular bundle at day 5 (Fig. 3), thereby blocking the phloem channels and preventing GQDs from the translocation to the roots. The movement of NPs in plants was not only associated with the initial particle size, but also with the aggregation size (Hong et al., 2014). A study by Lin et al. (2009) reported that the large aggregates originated from individual C70 NPs could block the vascular system, thereby limiting the downward transport of NPs. In addition, Avellan et al. (2019) reported that AuNPs with a nominal size <50 nm could not only reach plant roots but also be exuded into the surrounding soils, regardless of their coating. Thus, the disappearance of GQDs transported to the roots earlier might be attributed to exudation into the rhizosphere soils. Overall, the schematic diagram for the translocation pathway is depicted in Fig. 4
                        . GQDs deposited on the leaves entered inner tissues via stomatal opening, and then efficiently moved down to the roots through phloem. The occurrence of GQDs aggregates in the stems significantly restricted the translocation of aggregates and dispersed particles to the roots due to their blockage to vascular bundles. Additionally, the larger aggregates of NH2-GQDs (+) led to a lower transfer efficiency in the whole plant than OH-GQDs (−).

For in-depth understanding the regulatory mechanisms responsible for the effects, the chlorophyll fluorescence parameters were measured for evaluating the damage to plant photosynthetic system (Baker, 2008; Kalaji et al., 2016). As shown in Fig. 5
                        , the F0 value increased continuously over the entire exposure period. For instance, after 8 days of NH2-GQDs and OH-GQDs treatments, the F0 increased by 132.7% and 158.5%, respectively (P < 0.05). Additionally, the images of chlorophyll fluorescence also demonstrated that F0 increases more prominently under OH-GQDs treatment compared with NH2-GQDs (Fig. 6
                        ). Therefore, OH-GQDs induced greater damage to PSII relative to NH2-GQDs. The possible mechanism for the increase of basic chlorophyll fluorescence was that the energy transfer efficiency of light-harvesting complex to PSII center decreased significantly (Kummerova et al., 2006).
